William D. Cohan
William D. Cohan

* Got an idea for
you, Brian!: Peter Supino, the respected media analyst at Wolfe Research (a=
nd the nephew of my former boss at Lazard), fired a ballsy warning shot at =
Comcast C.E.O. Brian Roberts this week. In an open letter, Supino suggested=
 that Comcast=E2=80=99s controlling shareholder break up his company into t=
hree parts=E2=80=94going much further than Brian=E2=80=99s decision to crea=
te a =E2=80=9Cwell-capitalized=E2=80=9D SpinCo composed of NBCU=E2=80=99s c=
able networks, including both
CNBC and MSNBC but minus Bravo. The Supino thesis, a considerable expansion=
 on an idea he first floated five years ago, calls for carving out Comcast=
=E2=80=99s cable distribution business and combining NBCU and Sky News, in =
addition to creating SpinCo.

Notably, Supino=E2=80=99s open letter followed Comcast=E2=80=99s disappoint=
ing fourth-quarter earnings report, which revealed larger-than-anticipated =
losses in broadband subscribers, plus flat subscriber growth in its streami=
ng business, causing the stock to
tumble 11 percent in one day. (My partner Matt Belloni offered an acute ana=
lysis, as ever, in his recent piece Kabletown at a Krossroads ( https://puc=
k.news/peacock-is-still-losing-money-what-should-comcast-do/?utm_campaign=
=3DIn+the+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F5%2F25%29&utm_content=3DIn+The+Room+-+S=
UBSCRIBERS+%282%2F5%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer=
=2Eio&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ).)

Supino=E2=80=99s note was unprecedented for its audacity, given the fact th=
at the guy is challenging a seasoned management team from his perch as an a=
nalyst rather than as an activist
investor with his own capital at stake. And, to be fair, it was filled with=
 compelling ideas. For instance, Supino pointed out that Comcast peers Disn=
ey, WBD, and Charter all trade at higher EBITDA multiples. (Disney trades a=
t 13x estimated 2025 EBITDA, WBD trades at 6.7x, and Charter at 6.5x. Comca=
st, meanwhile, trades at 5.7x.) He noted that if Comcast were weighted prop=
ortionately and traded at an average of its multiples, its stock would rise=
 57 percent. =E2=80=9CWe believe that
the market discounts Comcast=E2=80=99s value severely because of concerns a=
bout returns on capital and instances of misalignment of leadership and sha=
reholders,=E2=80=9D he wrote. =E2=80=9CWe truly believe that as long as Com=
cast persists as a conglomerate, such concerns are likely to hamper the sto=
ck.=E2=80=9D (Usual disclosure: This is not investment advice.)

Supino doesn=E2=80=99t see much growth potential in Xfinity, or from the br=
oadcast networks, the cable networks, Peacock, and Sky, unless equity incen=
tives are
reshuffled to better align leadership and shareholders. He was also highly =
critical of Comcast=E2=80=99s M&A strategy, estimating that Comcast spent $=
93 billion to acquire NBCU and Sky and to stand up Peacock, and that togeth=
er they generate $7.5 billion of EBITDA, which the market values at 5.7x EB=
ITDA, or $43 billion=E2=80=94=E2=80=9Ca $50 billion mark-to-market loss,=E2=
=80=9D he wrote. He was also critical of Brian=E2=80=99s $340 million in cu=
mulative compensation over the past 10 years and failure to invest in the C=
omcast stock
during that time. His 40.8 million Comcast shares represent 1 percent of th=
e shares outstanding. Meanwhile, he controls 31 percent of the vote.=C2=A0

Supino wrapped up his jeremiad with some familiar notions. =E2=80=9CWe beli=
eve Comcast=E2=80=99s financial strength has provided false comfort to NBCU=
, and that the business independently funds its own growth investments,=E2=
=80=9D he wrote. =E2=80=9CWhile Universal has made great films and theme pa=
rks under Comcast and while Peacock is a beautiful service, NBC Universal
was late to streaming and lacks the scale to win against YouTube, Netflix, =
Amazon, and Disney. NBCU=E2=80=99s EBITDA of more than $7B is more than eno=
ugh to fund growth and negotiate potential strategic mergers.=E2=80=9D

Anyway, dividing Comcast into three parts is an interesting idea, to be hon=
est, and one that Brian should consider seriously, even if he likely won=E2=
=80=99t. Supino texted me yesterday that his report =E2=80=9Celicited more =
reads than any company-specific report I=E2=80=99ve ever published. It=E2=
=80=99s the only time
in my career I=E2=80=99ve ever written an opinion that elicited 100 percent=
 positive feedback.=E2=80=9D A spokesman for Comcast declined to comment.

